TITLE: Handling Localized 404 Pages in gatsby-node.js (JavaScript)
DESCRIPTION: This code snippet modifies the onCreatePage API in gatsby-node.js to handle localized 404 pages. It checks if a page path matches the format '/[language-code]/404/'. If it does, it updates the page's matchPath property to match all paths with that language code, effectively routing non-existent pages to the corresponding localized 404 page. It requires the 'actions' object from Gatsby.
SOURCE: https://github.com/gatsbyjs/gatsby/blob/master/docs/docs/creating-prefixed-404-pages-for-different-languages.md#_snippet_2

LANGUAGE: JavaScript
CODE:
```
exports.onCreatePage = async ({ page, actions }) => {
  const { createPage, deletePage } = actions

  // Check if the page is a localized 404
  if (page.path.match(/^\/[a-z]{2}\/404\/$/)) {
    const oldPage = { ...page }

    // Get the language code from the path, and match all paths
    // starting with this code (apart from other valid paths)
    const langCode = page.path.split(`/`)[1]
    page.matchPath = `/${langCode}/*`

    // Recreate the modified page
    deletePage(oldPage)
    createPage(page)
  }
}
```

